      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B02",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Millikan's measurements made the contradiction sharp. Increase the intensity below a metal's threshold: the current remains zero. Use light above threshold: emission begins without a classical charging delay.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B02.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.86,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B02.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B03",
      "estimated_duration_s": 9,
      "narration_text": "Classical wave reasoning says greater intensity delivers more energy per second. An electron should accumulate that energy, wait long enough, and escape. The experiment refuses.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B03.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 10.84,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B03.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B04",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "That classical picture treats illumination as a continuous energy stream. Turning up the amplitude should fill an electron's energy account faster. Below threshold, no such accumulation appears.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "accumulate"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B04.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.43,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B04.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B05",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The decisive variable is frequency. Below a sharp threshold frequency, ordinary single-photon emission is absent. Above it, the maximum electron kinetic energy rises linearly with frequency, not intensity.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B05.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.03,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B05.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B06",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "The mechanism is indivisible packets of light.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B06.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 3.37,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B06.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B07",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "Each photon carries energy h nu. In the basic photoelectric event, one photon transfers energy to one electron. If that energy cannot clear the surface barrier, extra brightness only supplies more individually inadequate photons.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "transfer"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B07.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 14.14,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B07.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B08",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Intensity mainly changes the incident photon rate. Above threshold, that can increase the emission rate. It does not raise the maximum kinetic energy, and real materials need not eject one electron for every incident photon.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B08.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 13.25,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B08.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B09",
      "estimated_duration_s": 6,
      "narration_text": "One photon supplies one energy packet. The threshold judges that packet.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "CARD",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "hold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B09.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 4.89,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B09.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B10",
      "estimated_duration_s": 11,
      "narration_text": "The work function phi is the minimum energy needed to remove an electron from the surface. When h nu exceeds phi, the largest possible kinetic energy is h nu minus phi.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "threshold"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B10.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 11.11,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B10.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B11",
      "estimated_duration_s": 10,
      "narration_text": "Plot maximum kinetic energy against frequency. The graph stays at no single-photon emission below nu naught, then rises with slope h. Increasing intensity changes counts, not this line's slope or intercept.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "scan"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B11.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 12.42,
      "build": {
        "status": "MANIM",
        "src": "manim/B11.mp4",
        "filled_by": "manim",
        "at": "2026-07-18T14:25:54"
      }
    },
    {
      "beat_id": "B12",
      "estimated_duration_s": 12,
      "narration_text": "For sodium, take a work function near 2.36 electron volts. A 620 nanometer red photon has about 2.00 electron volts: short by 0.36. A 400 nanometer violet photon has 3.10, leaving up to 0.74 electron volts.",
      "shot": {
        "type": "GRAPHIC",
        "source": "own",
        "motion": "compare"
      },
      "audio_file": "mp3/beat-B12.mp3",
      "actual_duration_s": 17.34,
